  "title": "Week 6 (2\/16 - 2\/20)",
  "body": " Week 6 (2\/16 - 2\/20)  This week we discuss the product and quotient rules (section 2.3) and then apply them to additional trig functions (section 2.4).   Monday 2\/16  We know how to take derivatives of a bunch of basic functions, as well as how to take derivatives of functions that are the sum or difference of those functions. The sum rule says that the derivative of a sum is just the sum of the derivatives. That is, if is the sum of two functions, we can find by taking the derivatives of each of the two functions and adding the results.  However, this is not true for products. On the one hand, we can quickly see that this fails if we take the derivative of . On one hand, we could simplify this function as , so . However, if we took the derivative of the two parts separately, we would have and . Multiplying those would give which is definitely not the same.  Another reason to be skeptical: suppose a magic rectangle has sides and , both of which are increasing with time. The area of the rectangle is then also a function of time. That is, .   Let's say that and . Then . How much new area do you get if increases by and increases by in the next day? Does the area just increase by ?    No, since growing to 23 doesn't just add 3 feet: we get area of more feet! And when the width increases by 4 feet, that adds more feet.    Draw the picture. Every increase in one dimension must be multiplied by the current size of the other dimension.    In other words, the increase is .     This gives us the product rule : if , then .  Do a few examples with functions we know. Start with .  Quotients have a similar rule: the quotient rule says that if then . We can prove this from the product rule by noting that . Apply the product rule and then solve for .  Try some examples.  Note that we can use both rules in the same function. A function that is the ratio of a product and another function, for example.    Tuesday 2\/17  Today we practiced additional examples of the product rule and the quotient rule, including an example where the product rule is required in the numerator of a quotient.    Wednesday 2\/18  Our goal today is to discover derivative rules for the rest of the main trigonometric functions: , , , and .  First, remember the Fundamental Trigonometric Identity : . This is just a version of the Pythagorean Theorem on the unit circle. We will use this to simplify the derivatives for the other trig functions.  Look at . In right triangles, is the ratio of the leg opposite the angle to the leg adjacent to it. But look at the unit circle, and remember that and , we have . So to find the derivative of we should apply the quotient rule to that ratio.  Similarly, we can do this for all the other functions. Go through them.    Friday 2\/20  Today we will do a little review about what we know how to do with derivatives already and explore the one way we don't yet know to take derivatives of combined functions.  Start with four warmup derivatives.  In the very few minutes left after that, we discussed what composition of functions looks like. This will help us understand the chain rule next week.   "
