  "title": "Week 10 (3\/23-3\/27)",
  "body": " Week 10 (3\/23-3\/27)   Monday 3\/23  Today we explore more of L'Hôpital's rule. The idea is that we can replace a function with its tangent line approximation and use this to evaluate the limit. But more precisely:   L'Hôpital's rule   Let and be differentiable on an open interval that includes and suppose that and that . Then     Let's do some examples:   Find .    Find .    Find .    Find .     Another use case for L'Hôpital's rule is to find end behavior of functions. That is, what happens to a function as gets arbitrarily large. We write this as . Here are some examples.   Find . What does this say about that function, and about the numerator and denominator separately.    Find     Find     Find .     Careful though. What is ? Or ? Try graphing these.    Tuesday 3\/24  Today we went over some more examples of L'Hopital's rule, mostly from the practice, including situations in which it is better to do some algebraic simplification first.    Wednesday 3\/25  We will start exploring the big application of derivatives: maximizing and minimizing a function. This starts with section 3.3, and will continue with 3.5 and 3.6 (we will skip 3.4).  Today we start by looking for local extrema. What we explore today will not really feel like an application, but hopefully it is not too much of a leap to think that the functions we have here could describe some real-world quantity (say cost or revenue) that we would like to minimize or maximize.  Start by looking at a graph that has local maxima, minimal, cusp points, and a saddle point. Consider what each of these are in terms of local extrema, global extrema, and values of the derivative.  What can we learn from this example? What is the connection between the local extrema a critical numbers : inputs at which the function has either derivative zero or no derivative?   If a function as a local max\/min at input , then either or does not exist. We call such a critical number , the point a critical point and the output a critical value     However, just because is a critical number, doesn't mean that has a local extrema at .    Why not? What can stop this from happening? This is where we use the first derivative near  to understand the behavior of the function.    The first derivative test says that if is a critical number of a continuous function that is differentiable near (except possibly at ), then we can look at the sign of on either side of to determine whether has a local maximum or minimum at . In particular, if changes from positive to negative at , then has a local maximum at . If changes from negative to positive at , then has a local minimum at .    We could also\/alternatively use the second derivative test : if is a critical number of a continuous function such that and , then has local maximum at if and only if and has a local minimum at if and only if .     Now lets see how this all works with an example. Consider . Find the critical numbers (factor), classify each using both tests, find points of inflection. Graph the function (by hand). Check that this makes sense by graphing with desmos.  Another example (needs quadratic formula) .    Friday 3\/27  Let's practice using the first and second derivative tests to explore the behavior of some functions, including finding local maxima and minima, intervals on which the function is increasing or decreasing, inflection points, and any asymptotes.  Start with an easier one: .  Next, try a slightly more complicated example: . Note we need to use the quotient rule here, and then factor the numerator to simplify it.  Another similar one: .   "
